Introduction to Open Data Science (Spring 2017)

Basics

This course is important for all data science students. Besides facilitating the learning of R in a systematic, well-structured manner, it teaches important tools for research sharing, version control and code maintenance.

https://muniandy.github.io/IODS-project/

Regression and Model Validation

In this chapter, we learnt how to read data from files and the internet. We also learnt how to explore the contents of the file, check the data types and visualize the data. Lastly, we learnt how to model our data using a linear regression model

  • We read in data from an URL, visualized the data and relationships between the variables and performed linear regression on selected data.

This dataset has 7 variables and 166 rows. This data comprised scores that belonged to three different types of questions i.e. - deep, strategic and surface questions. Each question type (deep, strategic, surface) has several questions linked to it. - For each group of questions, the average score was calculated and assigned to variables deep, stra and surf. - For each row, the average of the three scores (deep, stra and surf) is in the variable points. - Other variables include gender, age and attitude.

This dataset has 110 females and 56 males. Mean age of the participants is 25.51. Amongst deep, stra and surf, the variable deep has the highest mean and median. Deep and stra are positively correlated with age and attitude while surf is negatively correlated with age and attitude. The highest correlation is between surf and deep (-0.324)

##

## lm(formula = points ~ attitude + stra + age, data = lrn14)

## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 10.89543    2.64834   4.114 6.17e-05 ***
## attitude     3.48077    0.56220   6.191 4.72e-09 ***
## stra         1.00371    0.53434   1.878   0.0621 .  
## age         -0.08822    0.05302  -1.664   0.0981 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.26 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2182, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2037 
## F-statistic: 15.07 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 1.07e-08

Amongst the 6 variables tested, only attitude, stra and age are significantly associated with points. Attitude has a high association (p-values < 0.001) while stra and age have lower p-values (0.05<p<0.1). For each unit of attitude, there is an increase in points by 3.48077 units. For every unit increase in stra, there is an increase in points by 1.003 unit. For every unit increase in age, there is a decrease in points by 0.08 units (negative association). R squared of 0.2 indicates the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable.

These two plots show that the assumptions of the linear model have not been violated. The residuals plot doesnt show any patterns. Hence the size of the errors are not dependent on the explanatory variables. QQ plot shows that the errors of the model are normally distributed. The residuals vs levarage plots shows a couple of values stand out and cause a high leverage.

Logistic Regression

In this chapter, we learnt how to read data from the internet and combine two data sets which do not have unique identifiers. We also learnt how to explore data with bar and box plots. Lastly, we learnt how to model our data using a linear regression model.

Summary of data

This dataset has 382 rows and 35 variables. There is general information about the students: school they belong to, sex, age, address and family size. There is also information about their parents, allocation of hours towards travel to school and studytime, some personal information about what the student is otherwise occupied with, health status (including alcohol consumption) and grades for Math and Portugese across 2 periods.

2. Hypothesis

Hypotheses to be tested 1. alcohol use is associated with the quality of family relationships. 2. alcohol use is associated with students freetime. 3. alcohol use is associated with health. 4. alcohol use is associated with sex.

## 1    FALSE   270    4.014815      3.125926    3.518519
## 2     TRUE   112    3.758929      3.455357    3.723214

Summary

Here, we see that there are 270 cases of low alcohol use and 112 cases of high alcohol use (more than 2 on a scale of 1-5). freetime - free time after school (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high) famrel - quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent) health - current health status (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good)

In the group of high alcohol use, the mean of quality of family relationships is 3.7 and for the group with low alcohol use, the mean of quality of family relationships is 4.0. In general, it can be surmised that low alcohol use may be associated with better family relationships.

Amongst students with low alcohol use, there is less free time (mean = 3.12) compared to students with higher alcohol use who seem to have more free time (mean = 3.46). Interestingly, low alcohol consumption students seem to enjoy worse health (mean = 3.5) than students who drink more (mean = 3.72)

## 4      M     TRUE    71    3.774648      3.521127    3.915493

Summary

With regards to sex, 157 females consume low amounts of alcohol and 41 females consume high amounts of alcohol. In the group of females who drink more, family relationship is worse ( 3.73), they have more freetime (mean=3.34) and they enjoy better health (3.39) as compared to females who drink less.

In the male group, there are 113 males who drink less and 71 males who drink more. The group that drinks more has less quality family relationships (mean=3.77), more freetime (mean=3.52) and also enjoy better healht (3.91) as compared to males who drink less. Males with high alcohol use have more free time and better family relationships and enjoy better health than females with high alcohol use.

5. Boxplots for selected variables

Summary

The median for quality of family relationships is the same for both males and females across both groups of alcohol use (median = 4). The upper quartile value is 5 in both sexes for students with low alcohol use and 4 for students with high alcohol use. The lowest value for family relationship (ignoring the outliers) is 3 for students with low alcohol consumption and 2 for students with high alcohol consumption.

The median for student freetime is 3 for males and females for students with low alcohol use and 3 for females and 4 for males in the group with higher alcohol use. The upper quartile value is 5 in both sexes.

The median for student health is 4 for students with high and low alcohol use. Mean health is higher for students with high alcohol comsumption.

6. Barplots for selected variables

Summary

The pattern for family relationship across sexes is the same. For freetime, the smallest number of females have the most freetime (5) and the smallest number of males have the lowest freetime (1). For health, the highest number of individuals have the healthiest status in both sexes. Across both sexes, there are more individuals with low alcohol use.

Family relationships and period 1 scores are negatively associated with alcohol use i.e.the lower the quality of family relationships, the higher the alcohol use. The most significant association is sex. With sex=females as the baseline in the intercept, the coefficient for males is 0.06 + 0.91=0.97. In summary, family relationships, student freetime, sex and period 1 scores are are significantly associated with high alcohol use.

9. predictions versus the actual values

##        
##         FALSE TRUE
##   FALSE   250   20
##   TRUE     94   18

Summary

The model is more accurate at predicting high alcohol use = FALSE. Out of 270 cases that were FALSE (high alcohol use) the model predicted 20 cases to be TRUE (high alcohol use) and 240 as false. Out of 112 cases that were TRUE (high alcohol use) the model predicted 94 cases to be false (high alcohol use) and 18 as true.
